        <br><br>
        <div class="h5">What Is Blockchain?</div>
        At its core, blockchain is a distributed, digital ledger that records transactions in a way that is secure, transparent, and immutable (cannot be changed). It is made up of a chain of blocks, where each block contains a set of transactions. These blocks are linked together in chronological order to form a chain.

        <br><br>
        <div class="h5">Key Characteristics:</div>

        1. Decentralized: No single entity controls the entire network.

        <br>
        2. Secure: Transactions are verified using cryptography.
        
        <br>
        3. Transparent: Everyone in the network can see the ledger.

        <br>
        4. Immutable: Once a transaction is recorded, it cannot be altered.

        <br>

        <br>

        <div class="h5 text-success">How does Blockchain Work?</div>
        1. Transactions
        Blockchain starts when a user (or node) initiates a transaction. This could be anything from transferring cryptocurrency, signing a contract, or even recording data.
        The transaction is represented digitally and broadcast to a peer-to-peer network of computers (called nodes).

        <br>
        <br>
        2. Verification
        These nodes then work together to validate the transaction through a process known as consensus.
        Different blockchains use different consensus mechanisms, such as Proof of Work (PoW) or Proof of Stake (PoS), to agree on which transactions are valid.
        
        <br>
        <br>
        3. Block Creation
        Once validated, the transaction is grouped with other transactions into a new block.
        This block is then added to the existing chain, creating an unbreakable link between the new block and the previous one.

        <br>
        <br>
        4. Immutable Ledger
        The transaction is now part of the blockchain and can no longer be altered or deleted, ensuring a secure and transparent record.


        Why Is Blockchain Important?
        Blockchain offers several benefits over traditional systems, making it a game-changer for a variety of industries:

        Security: The use of cryptography and decentralized validation ensures that no single point of failure exists, making it difficult for hackers to alter data.
        Transparency: Everyone in the network can access the same ledger, increasing trust among participants.
        Efficiency: Blockchain eliminates the need for intermediaries like banks, reducing transaction costs and time.
        Decentralization: It distributes control among multiple participants (nodes), avoiding central authority.
